[{"type":"paragraph","children":[{"type":"text","value":"Gen X and early Millennials (born 1960s-1980s) saw steady decline","position":{"start":{"line":36,"column":1},"end":{"line":36,"column":1}},"key":"zMJ2D8H0X9"}],"key":"bFMwYhNjrJ"}],"key":"MgQQxWz1Xu"},{"type":"listItem","spread":true,"position":{"start":{"line":37,"column":1},"end":{"line":38,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"paragraph","children":[{"type":"text","value":"Recent cohorts (born 1990s-2000s) show accelerating decline","position":{"start":{"line":37,"column":1},"end":{"line":37,"column":1}},"key":"cRV6DJxVBH"}],"key":"RPkFvkzPZT"}],"key":"IcJJy7PQDD"}],"key":"y18Yiwolib"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":39,"column":1},"end":{"line":39,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"But that’s only part of the story. Recent generations are also postponing childbearing. The following figure shows timing shifts—positive values mean having children later, negative means earlier.","position":{"start":{"line":39,"column":1},"end":{"line":39,"column":1}},"key":"na1UTlz6ne"}],"key":"cKMSLE0OT5"},{"type":"image","url":"/BayesFertility//build/timing_shift_effects-e28663f529365c9f6104d5e4acb17ac2.png","alt":"Timing Shifts by Cohort","position":{"start":{"line":41,"column":1},"end":{"line":41,"column":1}},"key":"hR517GXcmh","urlSource":"figs/timing_shift_effects.png"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":43,"column":1},"end":{"line":43,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"The transition is clear:","position":{"start":{"line":43,"column":1},"end":{"line":43,"column":1}},"key":"fI6aMqvPir"}],"key":"TNQGZ4QAuB"},{"type":"list","ordered":false,"spread":false,"position":{"start":{"line":45,"column":1},"end":{"line":48,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"listItem","spread":true,"position":{"start":{"line":45,"column":1},"end":{"line":45,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"paragraph","children":[{"type":"text","value":"Early cohorts (1930s-1940s): negative timing shifts, having children relatively early","position":{"start":{"line":45,"column":1},"end":{"line":45,"column":1}},"key":"uD4NACvGh6"}],"key":"V0z8SR1A48"}],"key":"V9GixdsRtp"},{"type":"listItem","spread":true,"position":{"start":{"line":46,"column":1},"end":{"line":46,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"paragraph","children":[{"type":"text","value":"Middle cohorts (1950s-1970s): near zero, stable timing","position":{"start":{"line":46,"column":1},"end":{"line":46,"column":1}},"key":"qpu2FOgDyQ"}],"key":"r9KymeN9YL"}],"key":"aNEmC59pB1"},{"type":"listItem","spread":true,"position":{"start":{"line":47,"column":1},"end":{"line":48,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"paragraph","children":[{"type":"text","value":"Recent cohorts (1980s-2000s): increasingly positive, postponing childbearing","position":{"start":{"line":47,"column":1},"end":{"line":47,"column":1}},"key":"BZMfJYSlmj"}],"key":"ffEEOXTKSx"}],"key":"qHcDGinYEz"}],"key":"Wv9hd1bD4d"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":49,"column":1},"end":{"line":49,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"The recent cohorts ...","position":{"start":{"line":49,"column":1},"end":{"line":49,"column":1}},"key":"DePeHBAPMX"}],"key":"hqOpZWgDGb"},{"type":"heading","depth":2,"position":{"start":{"line":51,"column":1},"end":{"line":51,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Validation","position":{"start":{"line":51,"column":1},"end":{"line":51,"column":1}},"key":"v8ghDAEevu"}],"identifier":"validation","label":"Validation","html_id":"validation","implicit":true,"key":"iKwAv7zDaw"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":53,"column":1},"end":{"line":53,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"We can validate the model on cohorts who have already completed their childbearing. The following figure compares our model’s estimates (for cohorts with observed data at most ages) against actual completed fertility from Census data.","position":{"start":{"line":53,"column":1},"end":{"line":53,"column":1}},"key":"pwVGWI9LV4"}],"key":"mhJUMDrN9C"},{"type":"image","url":"/BayesFertility//build/cfr_vs_actual-dcf14e41aec5690b12a3d30ed08f6eb7.png","alt":"CFR vs Census Data","position":{"start":{"line":55,"column":1},"end":{"line":55,"column":1}},"key":"nYApQuIbw9","urlSource":"figs/cfr_vs_actual.png"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":57,"column":1},"end":{"line":57,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"The agreement is nearly perfect—the mean absolute difference is just 0.003 children per woman. For cohorts where we have complete data, the model works very well.","position":{"start":{"line":57,"column":1},"end":{"line":57,"column":1}},"key":"ULqNBbUkLW"}],"key":"gXTCw5lSGU"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":59,"column":1},"end":{"line":60,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"But for the youngest cohorts we have limited data.\nFor the cohort born in 2000, we’ve only observed them from ages 15-24, covering just one-third of their reproductive span. For those born in 2009, we’ve only seen age 15—about 3% of their total reproductive years.","position":{"start":{"line":59,"column":1},"end":{"line":59,"column":1}},"key":"o8WXTBrQDa"}],"key":"cUe7n77KRa"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":62,"column":1},"end":{"line":62,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Projections for these cohorts rely on the model’s assumptions, not just on observed data. The model uses Gaussian random walks to model generational changes -- which assumes that in the absence of evidence, each cohort will be similar to the previous one.","position":{"start":{"line":62,"column":1},"end":{"line":62,"column":1}},"key":"ezzVPNyocg"}],"key":"piQplKKjnD"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":64,"column":1},"end":{"line":64,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Importantly, the model does ","position":{"start":{"line":64,"column":1},"end":{"line":64,"column":1}},"key":"KrFLR9vON1"},{"type":"emphasis","position":{"start":{"line":64,"column":1},"end":{"line":64,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"not","position":{"start":{"line":64,"column":1},"end":{"line":64,"column":1}},"key":"QXVsrB7cfK"}],"key":"zLIhnrrSmW"},{"type":"text","value":" extrapolate declining trends—it doesn’t assume the recent decline will continue indefinitely, but it also doesn’t assume trends will reverse. For the youngest cohorts, the projections tend to level off rather than continuing downward. If something changes dramatically—new policies, economic shifts, cultural reversals—actual fertility could differ substantially from these projections.","position":{"start":{"line":64,"column":1},"end":{"line":64,"column":1}},"key":"NKrFD3esPq"}],"key":"lT3Mi5Qc8F"},{"type":"heading","depth":2,"position":{"start":{"line":66,"column":1},"end":{"line":66,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Effect of Timing Shifts","position":{"start":{"line":66,"column":1},"end":{"line":66,"column":1}},"key":"WO8wdUAtKI"}],"identifier":"effect-of-timing-shifts","label":"Effect of Timing Shifts","html_id":"effect-of-timing-shifts","implicit":true,"key":"VNLhzndOi3"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":68,"column":1},"end":{"line":68,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"I tested several versions of this model. Version 3.0 is simpler—it just has cohort effects and age effects, without the timing shifts.  Version 4.0 fits the data substantially better, as we should expect with more parameters.","position":{"start":{"line":68,"column":1},"end":{"line":68,"column":1}},"key":"xUObswgPHZ"}],"key":"kgsHTDtwtw"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":70,"column":1},"end":{"line":70,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"The following figure compares their CFR projections:","position":{"start":{"line":70,"column":1},"end":{"line":70,"column":1}},"key":"KSBEBRJqBD"}],"key":"aJdgbdye4G"},{"type":"image","url":"/BayesFertility//build/comparison_cfr-882ed37c7bd51eeb42d5cb1372661db6.png","alt":"Model Comparison","position":{"start":{"line":72,"column":1},"end":{"line":72,"column":1}},"key":"pwF0Vyvpko","urlSource":"figs/comparison_cfr.png"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":74,"column":1},"end":{"line":74,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"For most cohorts, the projections are nearly identical. But for some younger cohorts, v4.0 projects slightly higher fertility.","position":{"start":{"line":74,"column":1},"end":{"line":74,"column":1}},"key":"BF3wZT1gfb"}],"key":"Jn2CiKY9AC"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":76,"column":1},"end":{"line":76,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"That said, the timing shifts alone aren’t enough to change the overall story -- the projections remain very low.","position":{"start":{"line":76,"column":1},"end":{"line":76,"column":1}},"key":"Jx9Q3TQbHn"}],"key":"zUn9ufbmlm"},{"type":"heading","depth":2,"position":{"start":{"line":78,"column":1},"end":{"line":78,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Implications","position":{"start":{"line":78,"column":1},"end":{"line":78,"column":1}},"key":"jJQPFUKjk4"}],"identifier":"implications","label":"Implications","html_id":"implications","implicit":true,"key":"pDA2ucFVPq"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":80,"column":1},"end":{"line":80,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"This rate of decline would have a range of implications:","position":{"start":{"line":80,"column":1},"end":{"line":80,"column":1}},"key":"PiisyXJ2ks"}],"key":"MlzdL7GIlE"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":82,"column":1},"end":{"line":82,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"strong","position":{"start":{"line":82,"column":1},"end":{"line":82,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Population dynamics","position":{"start":{"line":82,"column":1},"end":{"line":82,"column":1}},"key":"BVT9vrX3NF"}],"key":"iAgl0ubjo0"},{"type":"text","value":": Without increased immigration, the US population would decline significantly.","position":{"start":{"line":82,"column":1},"end":{"line":82,"column":1}},"key":"OvzqwVNNkA"}],"key":"NHfpXXtytI"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":84,"column":1},"end":{"line":84,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"strong","position":{"start":{"line":84,"column":1},"end":{"line":84,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Economic impacts","position":{"start":{"line":84,"column":1},"end":{"line":84,"column":1}},"key":"SuSR3UoXs0"}],"key":"ajreaYdcgE"},{"type":"text","value":": A smaller workforce relative to the number of retirees puts pressure on Social Security and Medicare. Housing demand shifts as fewer families form. School systems will need to adjust to smaller cohorts.","position":{"start":{"line":84,"column":1},"end":{"line":84,"column":1}},"key":"XAcPjaShKs"}],"key":"YU7bVvRJeT"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":86,"column":1},"end":{"line":86,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"strong","position":{"start":{"line":86,"column":1},"end":{"line":86,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Historical context","position":{"start":{"line":86,"column":1},"end":{"line":86,"column":1}},"key":"lcFzZe4Sd6"}],"key":"ejtzUn0tWH"},{"type":"text","value":": This rate of decline is comparable to the post-baby boom transition (1960s-1980s), but starting from a much lower baseline. The US has never seen fertility this low.","position":{"start":{"line":86,"column":1},"end":{"line":86,"column":1}},"key":"lHrLnTxa4w"}],"key":"P85gHRw4Hy"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":88,"column":1},"end":{"line":88,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"strong","position":{"start":{"line":88,"column":1},"end":{"line":88,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Policy questions","position":{"start":{"line":88,"column":1},"end":{"line":88,"column":1}},"key":"jmFmTtNWNr"}],"key":"T4Hup56fgH"},{"type":"text","value":": Understanding whether people want fewer children or face barriers to having children they want is crucial for policy responses. The model projections suggest recent cohorts will have fewer children, but they don’t tell us why.","position":{"start":{"line":88,"column":1},"end":{"line":88,"column":1}},"key":"Z4129iRJ9J"}],"key":"EMx3glRmHm"},{"type":"heading","depth":2,"position":{"start":{"line":90,"column":1},"end":{"line":90,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Summary","position":{"start":{"line":90,"column":1},"end":{"line":90,"column":1}},"key":"vrnVSgQnVx"}],"identifier":"summary","label":"Summary","html_id":"summary","implicit":true,"key":"i1KAZlDbMx"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":92,"column":1},"end":{"line":92,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Using Bayesian methods and nearly 50 years of fertility data, we can project cohort fertility rates for generations still in their reproductive years. The projections show dramatic declines ahead—potentially to historically unprecedented levels.","position":{"start":{"line":92,"column":1},"end":{"line":92,"column":1}},"key":"vhn2y2VbYo"}],"key":"UNLToUnDlc"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":94,"column":1},"end":{"line":94,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"These projections should be interpreted as “what we would expect if recent patterns persist,” not as definitive forecasts. Fertility can and does respond to changing circumstances. But demographic trends have momentum—they don’t reverse quickly or easily.","position":{"start":{"line":94,"column":1},"end":{"line":94,"column":1}},"key":"J9YTJmt4OZ"}],"key":"oqPNG9MThY"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":96,"column":1},"end":{"line":96,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Substantial uncertainty remains, especially for the youngest cohorts. We won’t know their actual completed fertility until the 2040s or 2050s. But the trends are consistent and clear: unless something changes, US fertility is heading for historic lows.","position":{"start":{"line":96,"column":1},"end":{"line":96